    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with a clear focus on maximizing high-upside matchups against mediocre arms. Our strongest play is **Mickey Moniak** (73.71), whose elite platoon advantage against Grant Holmes and a favorable park factor significantly outweigh his typical bottom-of-the-order penalty. Similarly, **Austin Riley** (73.69) is locked in for the UTIL slot, benefiting from a high-efficiency matchup against Jose Quintana; his projection is bolstered by a massive +19% SP skill advantage. **Brice Turang** (73.59) remains a high-floor engine, leveraging his position as a #2 hitter against Jake Irvin to provide consistent production across all five categories, particularly in the scarce SB department.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision involved **Tyler Soderstrom** (52.39), who narrowly missed the cut behind the slightly more favorable situational profiles of **Kyle Karros** and **James Wood**. While **Tyler Soderstrom** offers power upside, the optimizer penalized him for the dynamic platoon risk against Joey Cantillo, effectively pushing him to the bench in favor of guys with more favorable park environments. We are also keeping a close eye on **Corbin Carroll** (71.61) and **Seiya Suzuki** (61.54); while both are strong starts, they carry \"Wind In\" warnings that could suppress home run potential at the margins. \n\nRisk management remains paramount, as nearly our entire starting lineup relies on assumed batting positions. We are especially cautious with **Corbin Carroll**, whose elite speed profile is hampered by a 4% hold penalty against the pitcher's efficiency, and **James Wood**, whose matchup against Jacob Misiorowski (xERA 3.28) is the most challenging of the day. If confirmed lineups shift **Luis Campusano** or **Dalton Rushing** out of their anticipated slots, we may see further fluctuations in their efficiency scores, though they remain our primary options behind the plate to maintain necessary game-cap discipline.